# Git Workflow Rules (MANDATORY)

## Branch Protection

NEVER commit or push directly to `main` or `master`. This is enforced by git hooks, but you MUST also check proactively before any git operation:

1. Run `git rev-parse --abbrev-ref HEAD` to verify the current branch.
2. If on `main` or `master`, STOP. Create a feature branch first:
   ```
   git checkout -b feat/<short-description>
   ```
3. Push the feature branch and open a PR to merge into main.
4. **Hotfix escape hatch:** Only if a critical fix absolutely must go directly to main, use `git push --no-verify`. This should be extremely rare and deliberate.

## AI Co-Authoring

When you (an AI agent) create a git commit, you MUST include a `Co-Authored-By` trailer in the commit message. This is non-negotiable.

Format:
```
<commit message>

Co-Authored-By: <Agent Name> <noreply@<provider>.com>
```

Examples:
- `Co-Authored-By: Cursor <noreply@cursor.com>`
- `Co-Authored-By: Claude Sonnet 4.6 <noreply@anthropic.com>`
- `Co-Authored-By: GPT-4o <noreply@openai.com>`
- `Co-Authored-By: GitHub Copilot <noreply@github.com>`

This applies to ALL commits: new commits, amends, fixups, and squash commits.
